Undid revision 832235171 by [[Special:Contributions/Dimadick|Dimadick]] ([[User talk:Dimadick|talk]]) Actress and Actor are different terms. Yellow is a common term for people of Oriental descent, and is not used in a derogatory or negative manner.
Removed redirect to other page as "Blackwashing" is NOT the same as "Color-blind casting".

/* List of films */ Fixed the problem of people being referred to as being "white" while simultaneously listing the ethnic background of non-white people; i.e. if you say someone is white (based on the color of their skin), then you must refer to others by their skin color also. Saying that an "African-American" person is portrayed by a "white" person is incorrect and mixes terminology; if you refer to someone as "African-American" then you must refer to others by their country of origin also i.e. "Irish-American", "Polish-American", "German-American", "Russian-American" etc. - if you refer to someone as "white", the appropriate terminology for non-white people would be to describe them based on their skin color - yellow, red, black, brown, etc. "Black" people are not necessarily "African-American", and "African-American" people are not necessarily "black".

"Native Americans have also been subjected to this, seeing their historic leaders and warriors portrayed by whites.[4]" Saying that someone has "been subjected to" something implies that it could not be avoided; Native Americans were not forced to watch films. Also changed 'whites' to 'people with light skin' as 'whites' could be misinterpreted as referring to albinos.

/* List of films */ "In the superhero film featuring Batman, actor Liam Neeson plays Ra's al Ghul, who is traditionally depicted in Batman comics to be of Arab descent." Since 1944, Arabs have been deemed "white" by law. Liam Neeson is Irish-American, and also considered to be "white". A "white" actor portraying a "white" character does not constitute "whitewashing”.

/* List of films */ In the historical film "The Wind and the Lion" actor Sean Connery plays Mulai Ahmed er Raisuni, a leader of Berber insurrectionists. The United States Census Bureau defines "white" people as those "having origins in any of the original peoples of Europe, the Middle East, or North Africa." This includes Berbers. Since both Berbers and English are considered "white", this is not an example of "whitewashing”.
